<subSubSection id="3BD2EEFA91E923569447AB855E21A49C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2685B3BBA14575E6F05FEF881B825ED3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FBB7C9D1D5383E0630A6BB08E9194685" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Very small beetles, body length 1.15-1.45 mm. Body shape oval in dorsal view; slightly to moderately, and evenly convex in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="75941A1B25B5A8F80C01C5686A36359E" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figure 41. Habitus of Nanosaphes spp. A-C N. tricolor: A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus C ventral habitus D-F N. punctatus: D dorsal habitus E lateral habitus F ventral habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1045.63810.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/557440" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">41</figureCitation>
). Coloration uniformly brown, to variable along the body; ground punctation shallow to moderately marked (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2310E643EAA535E151D87647DA1678EB" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figure 41. Habitus of Nanosaphes spp. A-C N. tricolor: A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus C ventral habitus D-F N. punctatus: D dorsal habitus E lateral habitus F ventral habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1045.63810.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/557440" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">41</figureCitation>
). Shape of head trapezoid and relatively wide. Eyes moderate in size, slightly emarginated anteriorly, not projected from outline of head. Clypeus trapezoid, with anterior margin broadly emarginate. Labrum fully exposed. Mentum with lateral oblique ridges. Antennae with eight antennomeres; cupule slightly asymmetric, with rounded outline. Maxillary palps slender, moderately long nearly 0.7 
<normalizedToken id="839BD16300671D00706E91EC10124D00" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
the width of head; inner margin of maxillary palpomere 2 nearly straight, outer margin curved along apical half (e.g., Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D93E2F5924437FFC1A416B4F796F7D40" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figure 41. Habitus of Nanosaphes spp. A-C N. tricolor: A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus C ventral habitus D-F N. punctatus: D dorsal habitus E lateral habitus F ventral habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1045.63810.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/557440" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">41C, F</figureCitation>
). Each elytron with ground punctures usually only shallowly marked, seemingly forming longitudinal rows, with irregularly distributed systematic punctures bearing rather long setae, denser along lateral and posterior regions; elytra without sutural striae. Prosternum flat, at most only weakly convex. Posterior elevation of mesoventrite, usually projected as low and short longitudinal carina between mesocoxae; anapleural sutures only weakly curved, separated at anterior margin by distance nearly 0.9 
<normalizedToken id="047561C83C8F4442BDAC11CF8989BCD4" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
width of anterior margin of mesepisternum. Metaventrite with posterolateral and mesal glabrous patches (e.g., Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E7D7FFD58E6EC580358AFBABF447B1A3" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figure 41. Habitus of Nanosaphes spp. A-C N. tricolor: A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus C ventral habitus D-F N. punctatus: D dorsal habitus E lateral habitus F ventral habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1045.63810.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/557440" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">41C, F</figureCitation>
). Protibiae with spines of anterior row hair-like, semi erect, relatively long, thick and sparse. Metafemora mostly densely covered by hydrofuge pubescence (e.g., Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F3F80CBBAEA033B9AC4C5094DB07839B" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figure 41. Habitus of Nanosaphes spp. A-C N. tricolor: A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus C ventral habitus D-F N. punctatus: D dorsal habitus E lateral habitus F ventral habitus. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1045.63810.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/557440" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">41C, F</figureCitation>
). All tarsomeres with long and thick spines on ventral faces of tarsomeres 2-4; metatarsomeres 2-4 gradually decreasing in size, metatarsomere 5 as long as 3 and 4 combined, 2 slightly shorter. Fifth abdominal ventrite apically emarginate, with fringe of stout setae. Aedeagus trilobed (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FA43031C74C4E3FB63665FB1F5F531DC" captionStart="Figure 40" captionStartId="F40" captionText="Figure 40. Aedeagi of Katasophistes and Nanosaphes spp. A K. charynae B K. cuzco C K. merida D K. superficialis E N. tricolor F N. hesperus G N. castaneus H N. punctatus. Scale bars: 0.3 mm (A-C); 0.1 mm (E-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1045.63810.figure40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/557439" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">40E-H</figureCitation>
), nearly parallel sided, with basal piece 0.3-0.6 
<normalizedToken id="CE359D0151F323DEACCF87C67E49DECF" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of parameres; median lobe with well-developed lateral basal apodemes, wider at base than base of each paramere, usually narrower at apex than preapical width of parameres; apex of median lobe rounded; parameres from slightly shorter to longer than median lobe, and only narrowing at apex; gonopore situated beyond midpoint of median lobe.
</paragraph>
